<li id="cite_note-61"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-61">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation book">Huddleston, Rodney; Pullum, Geoffrey K. (2002). <i><a href="The_Cambridge_Grammar_of_the_English_Language" title="The Cambridge Grammar of the English Language">The Cambridge Grammar of the English Language</a></i>. Cambridge, UK: <a href="Cambridge_University_Press" title="Cambridge University Press">Cambridge University Press</a>. p.&#160;610. <a href="International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="Special_BookSources/0-521-43146-8" title="Special:BookSources/0-521-43146-8">0-521-43146-8</a>.</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-New_Oxford-62"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-New_Oxford_62-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-New_Oxford_62-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">New Oxford Dictionary of English, 1999, usage note for <i>an</i>: "There is still some divergence of opinion over the form of the indefinite article to use preceding certain words beginning with <b>h</b>- when the first syllable is unstressed: ‘<b>a</b> historical document’ or ‘<b>an</b> historical document’; ‘<b>a</b> hotel’ or ‘<b>an</b> hotel’. The form depends on whether the initial h is sounded or not: <b>an</b> was common in the 18th and 19th centuries because the initial h was commonly not pronounced for these words. In standard modern English the norm is for the <b>h</b> to be pronounced in words such as <b>hotel</b> and <b>historical</b> and therefore the indefinite article <b>a</b> is used; however the older form, with the silent <b>h</b> and the indefinite article <b>an</b>, is still encountered, especially among older speakers."</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Peterspg1-63"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Peterspg1_63-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Peterspg1_63-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="Brown_Corpus" title="Brown Corpus">Brown Corpus</a> and <a href="Lancaster-Oslo-Bergen_Corpus" title="Lancaster-Oslo-Bergen Corpus">Lancaster-Oslo-Bergen Corpus</a>, quoted in Peters (2004: 1)</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-64"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-64">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://grammar.ccc.commnet.edu/grammar/determiners/determiners.htm#articles">"Articles, Determiners, and Quantifiers"</a>. Grammar.ccc.commnet.edu<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://grammar.ccc.commnet.edu/grammar/determiners/determiners.htm#articles">http://grammar.ccc.commnet.edu/grammar/determiners/determiners.htm#articles</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 2010-11-07</span>.</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-65"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-65">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Algeo, p. 49.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-66"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-66">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.oup.com/oald-bin/web_getald7index1a.pl?nav=on&which_entry=008170%23x1%23x2%23cookbook&selected_word=cookbook&search_word=cookery">"''Cookbook'' is now often used in BrE"</a>. Oup.com<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.oup.com/oald-bin/web_getald7index1a.pl?nav=on&which_entry=008170%23x1%23x2%23cookbook&selected_word=cookbook&search_word=cookery">http://www.oup.com/oald-bin/web_getald7index1a.pl?nav=on&amp;which_entry=008170%23x1%23x2%23cookbook&amp;selected_word=cookbook&amp;search_word=cookery</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 2010-11-07</span>.</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-67"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-67">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Crystal states one of the classification problems as</span>
<dl>
<dd>
<dl>
<dd><span class="reference-text">"We have to allow for words which have at least one [shared] meaning and one or more additional meanings that are specific to either AmE or BrE: an example is caravan, which in the sense of 'group of travellers in the desert' is common to both varieties; but in the sense of 'vehicle towed by a car' it is BrE (=AmE trailer)"</span></dd>
</dl>
</dd>
</dl>
<span class="reference-text">David Crystal, The Cambridge Encyclopaedia of The English Language. 2nd Edition. (Cambridge University Press, 2003)</span></li>
